ographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Brailsford","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (East Midlands and Yorkshire): habitational name from a place in Derbyshire named Brailsford, possibly from an Old English word <i>brægels</i>, a metathesized form of <i>bærgels</i>, itself a byform of <i>byrgels</i> ‘tumulus, barrow’, + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’."],"variants":[{"name":"Brelsford","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Brailsford  ."]}]},{"name":"Henry","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["A perennially popular given name, of Continental Germanic origin, from <i>haim</i> ‘home’ + <i>rīc</i> ‘power, ruler’. It was an Old French name, adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. It has been borne by eight kings of England. Not until the 17th century did the form <i>Henry</i> (as opposed to   Harry  ) become the standard vernacular form, mainly under the influence of the Latin form <i>Henricus</i> and French <i>Henri</i>."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Henry de Brailsford was born in 1259, his father, Henry de Brailsford III, was 53 and his mother, Isabel Picot, was 29. He married Joan in 1284, in Brailsford Green, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters. He died in 1304, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1259–1304":"1259–1304","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","1253–1287":"1253–1287","1272–Female":"1272–Surnud","1264–Female":"1264–Surnud","1277–1344":"1277–1344","1279–Female":"1279–Surnud","1287–Male":"1287–Surnud","1289–1322":"1289–1322","1206–1258":"1206–1258","1230–Female":"1230–Surnud","1264":"1264","1253":"1253","1230":"1230","1284":"1284","1272":"1272","1206":"1206","1304":"1304","1259":"12